Each segment has:
  • "master_text"  — English OCR text from on-screen subtitles (authoritative; what is DISPLAYED)
  • "context_text" — English ASR transcript (what was SPOKEN; auxiliary, may have errors)
  • "start" / "end" — exact timestamps to preserve in output

━━ YOUR TASK ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1.  **Output the OCR subtitle** (default, highest priority)
    "master_text" is the burned-in on-screen subtitle — the authoritative source.
    Output it as-is in the vast majority of cases.

    Decision rule:
      • master_text present → output it directly.
      • master_text empty or missing, context_text (ASR) available → use ASR verbatim.
      • Both present but differ → trust master_text (OCR); use ASR only to resolve
        obvious OCR extraction errors (garbled characters, partial text, misread glyphs).
      • Both unintelligible → output master_text verbatim without inventing.

2.  **Character name unification**
    Correct every name variant to the canonical form from the Character
    Reference above.

3.  **No rewriting** — do NOT paraphrase, expand, or change the meaning of
    any line.  Preserve every segment's start/end timestamp exactly.
    You MAY merge consecutive segments when at least one has duration ≤ 0.3 s:
    concatenate the text with a single space and use the first start / last end
    timestamp.  Do NOT split segments.

━━ OUTPUT FORMAT ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
Return a valid SRT file ONLY.  Rules:
  • Sequence numbers start at 1 and increment by 1.
  • One blank line between every subtitle block — none inside a block.
  • Timestamp format exactly: HH:MM:SS,mmm --> HH:MM:SS,mmm
  • Use timestamps from the input JSON unchanged.
  • No code fences, no prose commentary, no explanatory notes.

